  {
    "@type": "FAQPage",
    "mainEntity": [
      {
        "@type": "Question",
        "name": "Can I replace a tripping 16A MCB with a 32A MCB to solve the problem?",
        "acceptedAnswer": { "@type": "Answer", "text": "Never. Upsizing the breaker without upgrading the wiring is one of the most dangerous DIY mistakes. The wire will overheat long before the 32A breaker reacts — the breaker is protecting the wire, not the appliances." }
      },
      {
        "@type": "Question",
        "name": "How many times can an MCB trip before it needs replacing?",
        "acceptedAnswer": { "@type": "Answer", "text": "A quality MCB (Schneider, Legrand, Siemens) is rated for 10,000 mechanical operations and 6,000 electrical operations under normal conditions. In practice, frequent short-circuit trips (which involve an arc flash inside the breaker) degrade it faster. If your MCB has tripped more than 20–30 times due to short circuits or severe overloads, it is worth having an electrician test it with a clamp meter." }
      },
      {
        "@type": "Question",
        "name": "Why does my AC only trip the breaker after 10–15 minutes?",
        "acceptedAnswer": { "@type": "Answer", "text": "This is a classic slow thermal overload. The MCB's internal bimetallic strip heats up gradually as the circuit slightly exceeds its rating. Causes include: other appliances sharing the same AC circuit, low line voltage forcing the compressor to draw more amps, dirty condenser coils overworking the motor, or a slightly undersized MCB." }
      },
      {
        "@type": "Question",
        "name": "What is the difference between an MCB and an RCCB/ELCB tripping?",
        "acceptedAnswer": { "@type": "Answer", "text": "An MCB (Miniature Circuit Breaker) protects copper wiring from overloads and short circuits — it reacts to too much current. An RCCB (Residual Current Circuit Breaker) or ELCB detects even a tiny current leak to ground (as small as 30 mA) to protect human beings from electric shock — not wiring damage." }
      },
      {
        "@type": "Question",
        "name": "Can a tripping MCB damage my appliances?",
        "acceptedAnswer": { "@type": "Answer", "text": "A thermal trip (overload) is gentle enough that most appliances are unaffected — the MCB simply cuts power before wires get hot. A magnetic trip (short circuit) is violent and can sometimes damage sensitive electronics connected to that circuit. Computers, TVs, and smart devices are at mild risk during a hard short-circuit trip. Using a surge protector on sensitive electronics is always advisable." }
      },
      {
        "@type": "Question",
